data.title: Musicians Born on February 1
data.meta_description: Famous birthdays in music for the 1st of February. See which composers, musicians, pop stars and rockers were born on February 1.
data.text:
Gabriel Schütz, German musician, composer, and teacher, born in the Free Imperial City of Lübeck (d. 1710)

Miguel Lopez, Spanish composer and organist, born in Villarroya de la Sierra, Aragon, Spain (d. 1723)

Alessandro Marcello, Italian composer, born in Venice, Republic of Venice (d. 1747)

Johann Adam Birkenstock, German composer and violinist, born in Alsfeld, Landgraviate of Hesse-Darmstadt, Holy Roman Empire (d. 1733)

Francesco Maria Veracini, Italian opera composer, born in Florence, Grand Duchy of Tuscany (d. 1768)

Hippolyte-André-Baptiste Chélard, French violist, composer and conductor, born in Paris, France (d. 1861)

Charles-Joseph Sax, Belgian music instrument builder of wind and brass instruments whose son invented the saxophone, born in Dinant, Wallonia, Belgium (d. 1865)

Adolf Fredrik Lindblad, Swedish lieder and classical composer, born in Skänninge, Sweden (d. 1878)

Emil Hartmann, Danish organist and composer (Towards The Light), born in Copenhagen, Denmark (d. 1898)

Victor Herbert, American cellist, composer, and conductor (Babes in Toyland; Eileen), born in Guernsey, Bailiwick of Guernsey (d. 1924) [he believed he was born in Dublin, Ireland] [1]

Clara Butt, British contralto (Country of Hope & Glory; Elgar's "Sea Pictures"), born in Southwick Sussex, England (d. 1936)

Thomas Frederick Dunhill, British composer (The Wind Among The Reeds), and teacher, born in London, England (d. 1946)

Antonio Guarnieri, Italian cellist and opera conductor (La Scala, 1929-50), born in Venice, Kingdom of Italy (d. 1952)

1880 Francesco Balilla Pratella, Italian composer, born in Lugo, Italy (d. 1955)

José Ignacio Quintón, Puerto-Rican composer (El coquí; Requiem por Angel Mislán), born in Caguas, Puerto Rico (d. 1925)

Rudolf Mengelberg, Dutch composer and musicologist (Amsterdam Concert Hall), born in Krefeld, Germany (d. 1959)

James P. Johnson, American pianist and composer ("The Charleston"; "If I Could Be With You (One Hour Tonight)"), born in New Brunswick, New Jersey (d. 1955)

Carlo Borbolla, Cuban pianist, organist, and composer, born in Manzanillo, Cuba (d. 1990)

Langston Hughes

American poet (Weary Blues), playwright (Mulatto), and librettist (Troubled Island), born in Joplin, Missouri

(Joe) "Tricky Sam" Nanton, American trombonist and plunger-mute pioneer (Duke Ellington Orchestra), born in New York City (d. 1946)

Hildegarde [Sell], American cabaret vocalist (“Leave It To The Girls"; "Darling, Je Vous Aime Beaucoup"), born in Adell, Wisconsin (d. 2005)

1906 Pierre Capdevielle, French conductor, composer (Élégie de Duino), music critic (Monde musicale), and teacher, born in Paris (d. 1969)

(Mozart) Camargo Guarnieri, Brazilian composer, pedagogue, and conductor, born in Tietê, São Paulo (d. 1993)

Edward Staempfli, Swiss pianist, conductor, and composer, born in Bern, Switzerland (d. 2002)

1908 Gene Sheldon, American actor (Zorro - "Bernardo"), mime artist, and banjo player, born in Columbus, Ohio (d. 1982)

George Beverly Shea, Canadian-American Grammy Award-winning gospel singer (Billy Graham Crusades, 1947-2013), born in Winchester, Ontario (d. 2013)

Edward Simons, American classical violinist and conductor (Rockland Symphony, 1962-2017), born in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania (d. 2018)

1917 Mary Jane DeZurik, American country singer and hillbilly yodeler (The Cackle Sisters - National Barn Dance; Grand Ole Opry), born in Royalton, Minnesota (d. 1981)

Renata Tebaldi, Italian lyric soprano, born in Pesaro, Italy (d. 2004)

Ursula Mamlok (nee Meyer), German-American avant-garde composer, and teacher, born in Berlin, Germany (d. 2016)

Debbie Dean [Reba Smith], American pop singer and songwriter (Motown), born in Corbin, Kentucky (d. 2001)

Sadao Watanabe, Japanese jazz and bossa nova saxophonist, and flute player, born in Utsunomiya, Japan

Bob Shane, American folk vocalist (Kingston Trio - "Tom Dooley"), born in Hilo, Territory of Hawaii (d. 2020)

(Isaac) Don Everly, American rock and roll singer-guitarist (The Everly Brothers - "Bye, Bye Love"; "Wake Up Little Susie"; "When WIll I Be Loved"), born in Brownie, Kentucky (d. 2021)

1937 Ray Sawyer, American rock singer (Dr Hook - "The Cover of Rolling Stone"), born in Chickasaw, Alabama (d. 2018)

Jimmy Carl Black [Inkanish], American rock drummer (Mothers Of Invention, 1965-69; Muffin Men, 1993-2008), born in El Paso, Texas (d. 2008)

Claude François, French pop singer-songwriter ("Comme d'habitude"), born in Ismaïlia, Egypt (d. 1978)

1939 Del McCoury, American bluegrass guitarist and singer, born in York, Pennsylvania

1939 Joe Sample, American jazz and session keyboardist and composer (The Jazz Crusaders), born in Houston, Texas (d. 2014)

Tommy Duffy, American musician (Echoes), born in Brooklyn, New York

Ole Buck, Danish classical pianist and composer, born in Copenhagen, Denmark

Carol Neblett, American operatic soprano (Metropolitan Opera, 1979-93), born in Modesto, California (d. 2017)

Mike Brant, Israeli pop singer ("Laisse-moi t'aimer" ("Let Me Love You")), born in Famagusta, Cyprus (d. 1975)

1947 Normie Rowe, Australian pop singer ("Que Sera Sera"), and stage and TV actor (Sons and Daughters), born in Melbourne, Australia

Rick James

American funk musician ("Super Freak"), born in Buffalo New York

Mike Campbell, American rock guitarist (Tom Petty & the Heartbreakers - "Breakdown"), and producer, born in Panama City, Florida

1950 Rich Williams, American guitarist (Kansas ' "Carry On Wayward Son"), born in Topeka, Kansas

(Clide) "Sonny" Landreth, American blues and zydeco slide guitar player, born in Canton, Mississippi

1951 Fran Christina, American rock and blues drummer (Fabulous Thunderbirds, 1977-96; Marcia Ball), born in Westerly, Rhode Island

Chuck Dukowski, American punk rock (Black Flag), born in Long Beach, California

(Christine) "Exene" Cervenka, American punk rock singer and poet (X), born in Chicago, Illinois

Dennis Brown, Jamaican reggae singer ("Money In My Pocket"), born in Kingston, Jamaica (d. 1999)

Ottmar Liebert, German guitarist, songwriter, and producer (Nouveau Flamenco), born in Cologne, Germany

Tomoyasu Hotei, Japanese rock guitarist and songwriter, born in Takasaki, Japan

Dwayne Goettel, Canadian keyboardist and industrial-electronic music composer (Skinny Puppy), born in High Level, Alberta (d. 1995)

1964 Jani Lane [John Oswald], American heavy metal rock songwriter, and singer (Warrant - "Cherry Pie"), born in Akron, Ohio (d. 2011)

1964 Mario Pelchat, Canadian francophone singer, born in Dolbeau-Mistassini, Quebec

Lisa Marie Presley

American singer-songwriter ("Lights Out"), and daughter of Elvis, born in Memphis, Tennessee [1]

Joshua Redman, American jazz saxophonist, and composer, born in Berkeley, California

1969 Patrick Wilson, American drummer (Weezer - "Buddy Holly"), born in Norfolk, Virginia

Ron Welty, American drummer (The Offspring - "Pretty Fly, For A White Guy"), born in Long Beach, California

Kami [Ukyō Kamimura], Japanese drummer (Malice Mizer), born in Ibaraki, Japan (d. 1999)

Yuri Landman, Dutch instrument inventor and musician, born in Zwolle, Netherlands

Big Boi [Antwan André Patton], American musician (Outkast), born in Savannah, Georgia

Jason Isbell, American singer-songwriter (Drive-By Truckers), born in Green Hill, Alabama

1979 Valentin Elizalde, Mexican singer, born in Navojoa, Mexico (d. 2006)

Andrew VanWyngarden, American musician and singer (MGMT), born in Columbia, Missouri

Shellback [Karl Schuster], Swedish Grammy Award-winning pop record producer and songwriter, with Max Martin (Pink; Maroon 5; Taylor Swift; Avril Lavigne), born in Karlshamn, Sweden

Hurricane Chris [Dooley], American rapper, born in Shreveport, Louisiana

Laura Marling, British singer-songwriter, born in Eversley, England

Harry Styles

British pop singer (One Direction - "What Makes You Beautiful"; solo - "Sign of the Times"), born in Redditch, England
